children.subject: This is terrible 😭 how did that happen? Jason was one of the nicest people I ever met at Berkeley. He was such a nice guy full of energy, never hesitated to offer help to anyone. I took 61A,B, C, and CS 70. I'll miss you Jason so badly 😢.
Wow, rest in peace Jason. I will miss having you in my CSM section, probably one of the best, most dedicated students Berkeley has ever seen.

What a tragedy. I remember having great interactions with Jason in office hours for cs61b. He was very righteous and caring for everyone to get help and learn. We had a lot of great conversations in the third floor lobby of Soda hall. Hearing how much he loved cs61c and how excited he was to take more computer architecture/cpu design upper divs and how he truly found his passion made me so happy. How terrible it is to hear he passed away. Rest in peace friend.

I am fortunate enough to have mentored him in CS 70 Office Hour this past summer. He was always willing to help other students and he had such an inspiring effect on everyone around him including me. I sincerely respect his diligence and radiant personality. I had the chance to take EE 16B and CS 61C with him last semester. I remember how he stood out for students in EE 16B lecture and how we had wonderful conversations before 61c final. I haven't seen him since the first class of 152 this semester where I was delighted to know he had found his true passion in Computer Science. It has been a pleasure and an honor to have mentored you and worked with you. Farewell my friend.
Hi Ahmed! Jason and I were good friends and I was able to speak to his family and roommate about paying tribute to Jason. You may text me at 510-676-6767.
Any idea if there's a funeral or a way to pay tribute to Jason?

I am beyond shocked to hear that Jason passed away. I was lucky to have been Jason's mentor for CS 61A a while back. He was always the kindest person, the most jovial and the most willing to help others. His enthusiasm and his energy inspired me to become a better teacher, but more importantly, become a better person. Whenever I would bump into him outside Soda Hall, he always greeted me with a smile and we had amazing conversations together. It is really sad to hear that Jason passed away, and I lost a really good friend. I'll miss you. Rest in peace, Jason.

Rest in peace Jason. We transferred here the same semester and I've known him through 16A, 16B and we were partners last semester in 61C. I loved working with him, he was always smiling when I see him and is the friendliest person I know on this campus. I remember talking to him just last month about preparing for 105. I'll miss you buddy.

When I was an AI for 61B he and I discussed his design for the BYOW project. He just dove after every little detail full of curiosity. Over a year later we took 61C together and he thanked me for that conversation months later. He was one of the lost thoughtful and considerate students this school has ever seen. The last time I ever saw him he cracked a joke on the first day of 161 and made everyone laugh.

Jason would always brighten my day when we sat next to each other in 61B and 61C. He had a knack for bringing everyone around him together when we were struggling, and made all of us better for it. Rest In Peace
hi everyone! Please text me at 510-676-6767 if you would like to attend a remembrance event for Jason or would like someone to speak to! Thanks!

history.content: It feels like just yesterday we were discussing SIMD and parallelism in CS61C. You were always at EE16B homework party last semester, contributing and learning from others and bringing a positive presence. You stood up for students, and you were an open friend to your peers. I wish I had gotten to know you better - you will be missed.
history.subject: Rest In Peace Jason Rossilli
